			<p>P IIId No 633: <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">Escape</term> arranged by a <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">German</placeName><term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term></p>
			<p>Report</p>
			<p>The following declarations were made by a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject">Jewish
					refugee</term> who had recently arrived in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2658434/switzerland.html"
					>Switzerland</placeName>.</p>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject">refugee</term> was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-598" type="subject">arrested</term> in the streets of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2800867/bruxelles-capitale.html">Brussels</placeName> during a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-550" type="subject">round-up</term> of Jews and was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-616" type="subject">interned</term> in the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-1970" type="camp">camp at Malines</placeName>,<note type="gloss"
					>Mechelen</note>where he was kept for three days with thousands of Jewish <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>. Some of them had received an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-617" type="subject">order</term> to report to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term>, equipped with belongings and enough <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-834" type="subject">rations</term> for two weeks. The others had been
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-598" type="subject">arrested</term> like him in the street, with no
				advance warning.</p>
			<p>At the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-1970" type="camp">camp</placeName> the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term> under fourteen were separated from the
				adults, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term> over sixty were sent <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">home</term>. He does not know what happened to the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>.</p>
			<p>After three days at the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-1970" type="camp">camp</placeName> he was
				designated for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deportation</term> with many of the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>, most of them young. All they had
				with them was taken away. Those who had received official summonses and consequently had luggage with them had to leave it behind.
				They were only allowed to keep the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>.
				Those who had been <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-598" type="subject">arrested</term> in the street and
				had nothing with them were given a loaf of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
					>bread</term>. At the station, before they boarded the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522"
					type="subject">train</term>, there was a second inspection. Each person had to put into a basket any valuables he had on him:
				rings, watches, etc. From some of them the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html"
					>German</placeName> inspectors took <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject"
					>clothes</term> they took a liking to, handing over in exchange second-hand <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">shoes</term> or <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term>.</p>
			<p>After this last inspection they were herded into a dozen <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522"
					type="subject">cattle wagons</term>. Our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject"
					>refugee</term> was shoved into a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagon</term>
				with seventy other <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>. They were squeezed in
				like sardines in a tin. Impossible to sit or to move; they had to stay this way for two and a half days. No chance of answering calls
				of nature. After two and a half days the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject"
					>train</term> stopped at <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3101619/chorzow.html">Königshütte</placeName> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3082777/upper-silesia.html">Upper Silesia</placeName> and the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-940">train</term> was cleared. Several of the weaker <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-519" type="subject">deportees</term> had lost consciousness and our
				informer saw seven of these carried off.</p>
			<p>At the station they were given hot <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> from
				large tureens marked with <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-419">red crosses</orgName>. It was probably
				a distribution organised by the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-419">German Red Cross</orgName>. Then
				the <pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-WL16560633_03.jpg"/> fourteen- to twenty-year-olds, who made up about half the convoy, were taken away. It
				seems they were to work in heavy <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-937" type="subject">industry</term> and
				in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-937" type="subject">mines</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3101619/chorzow.html">Königshütte</placeName> and its surrounding area.</p>
			<p>Other <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-519" type="subject">deportees</term> got back into the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagons</term> where this time there was a bit more
				space and the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> set off towards the east.
				Our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject">refugee</term> recognised <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/702550/lviv.html">Lvov</placeName> (<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/702550/lviv.html"
					>Lemberg</placeName>), then <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/695781/rava-rus-ka.html">Rava-Russka</placeName> and a region
				of the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/690791/ukraine.html">Ukraine</placeName>. He was too exhausted to notice how long the
				journey lasted. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> stopped in
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2017370/russian-federation.html">Russia</placeName>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-519" type="subject">deportees</term> were gathered together at the
				station. Each one was asked if he was fit to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject"
					>work</term>. Half of them, about 150 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>
				mostly aged between twenty and thirty-five, said they were. The others said they were not and were taken away, whilst the first group
				got back on the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> and continued the
				journey for half a day more. Our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject">refugee</term> does
				not know exactly in which region they arrived. It was in a distant region, deep inside <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2017370/russian-federation.html">Russia</placeName> – he noticed a signpost indicating <q><placeName
						ref="http://www.geonames.org/472757/volgograd.html">Stalingrad</placeName> 50 km</q>, and whilst he was in this region he
				heard the noise of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1083" type="subject">bombing</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1081" type="subject">gunfire</term> two or three times, suggesting they
				were close to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1081" type="subject">battle field</term>.</p>
			<p>As soon as they arrived the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term> were taken in
				groups to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">huts</term> and were given <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">work clothes</term>. These were khaki <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1091" type="subject">uniforms</term> as worn by the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-433"><foreign xml:lang="de">Todt</foreign></orgName> teams, <note
					type="gloss">Translator’s note: <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-433"><foreign xml:lang="de"
							>Organisation Todt (OT)</foreign></orgName> was a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159"
						type="subject">Third Reich</term> civil and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject"
						>military</term> engineering group named after its founder, <persName
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000411">Fritz Todt</persName>, an engineer and senior Nazi. It was
					notorious for using <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">forced labour</term>.
					(Source: Wikipedia)</note>but without the armbands with the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-369"
					type="subject">swastika</term>. Our informer was put into a group of sixty <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>. Other teams worked in the same area as
				his, and he noticed nearby a group of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3017382/republic-of-france.html">French</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoners</term>, as he realised when he heard them
				speaking their language. A <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">German</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> confirmed to him later that this
				observation was correct.</p>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">huts</term> reserved for the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-519" type="subject">deportees</term> were the same as the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-438">German army</orgName> uses for its <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>. There were bunk beds, in threes.</p>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> was very hard. They were probably
				constructing fortifications for the eastern front. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826"
					type="subject">men</term> had to carry over a long distance heavy sacks of cement weighing more than fifty kilos. There were also
				large iron grids from which they made sort of anti-tank barriers. They were forced to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> for ten hours each day and since they had
				to walk for an hour to and from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">huts</term> to
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work site</term>, the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">working day</term> was in reality twelve hours, from
				six in the morning to six at night. After a few days some of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826"
					type="subject">men</term> were completely exhausted. Supervisors constantly harried the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>, as a certain number of square metres had
				to be completed daily. Talking was not allowed during <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943"
					type="subject">working hours</term>. They <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject"
					>worked</term> on Sundays the same as on weekdays, apparently not being allowed to rest until the fifth Sunday.</p>
			<pb n="4" facs="EHRI-ET-WL16560633_04.jpg"/>
			<p>As for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>, the men received a 900-gram loaf
				of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>, that is 225 grams per <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">man</term>, each day. At midday and in the evening,
				hot <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term>. In the morning, a blackish liquid
				called <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">coffee</term>, with a little <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">saccharine</term>. In the evenings they all fell
				asleep, exhausted. All conversation was forbidden. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-843" type="subject"
					>Writing</term> was not possible.</p>
			<p>For a week our informer <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> very hard like
				all the others. Then, as one of the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html"
					>German</placeName> drivers had disappeared, one of the supervising <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officers</term> asked if anyone knew how to drive. As
				he had <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> in the <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-001573">Ford</persName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929" type="subject">factories</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2800867/bruxelles-capitale.html">Brussels</placeName> our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject">refugee</term> was chosen and from then on drove this
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer’s</term> car, accompanying him on all
				his tours of duty. They came to like each other and the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886"
					type="subject">officer</term> was quite open with him. He was a young <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2921044/federal-republic-of-germany.html">German</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> of about twenty-five. He was
				originally from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2951839/bavaria.html">Bavaria</placeName>, and had already earned three stars;
				he had lost two brothers in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term> and had
				left behind a young <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">wife</term> and small <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term>. He said he was totally disgusted by the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term> and everything to do with it. It was
				his opinion that the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term> was already lost,
				and he hated the thought of what had been done, and was still being done, to the Jews.</p>
			<p>The information that follows came to our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101" type="subject"
					>refugee</term> from this <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term>. Having
				asked what had happened to the group of Jews who had arrived with his group and who had been found incapable of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">working</term>, he was told by the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> that they all been <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">executed</term>; the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> added that this was the fate of all
				those who, through exhaustion, could no longer <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject"
					>work</term>. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> was unhappy
				with this state of affairs, but could do nothing to prevent it. Our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-101"
					type="subject">refugee</term> begged him not to keep harassing the Jews at <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term>, but the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> explained that he had to do it, because
				he was obliged ensure that a certain quantity of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject"
					>work</term> was completed each day.</p>
			<p>The means of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-529" type="subject">exterminating</term> the Jews who were
				incapable of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term>, said the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term>, was to line them up against a wall and
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-536" type="subject">shoot</term> them, or if this was not possible,
				by <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">poisoning</term> their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>.</p>
			<p>Our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">man</term> spent two weeks with this <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term>, who behaved like a gentleman. At the
				end of this time, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> told him that a
				very rare chance of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escape</term> was available to
				him. Every two or three months a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> left
				for the west and the following day was the very day of its departure. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> insisted he should seize this chance,
				which would not recur. He himself hid him in a goods <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject"
					>wagon</term> full of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-843" type="subject">parcels</term> and sacks,
				he gave him plenty of provisions (<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>,
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">conserves</term> etc) for the journey and two
					<foreign xml:lang="de">Reichsmarks</foreign> (the currency of the occupation). He told him not to worry about his <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1091" type="subject">uniform</term>, that these <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1091" type="subject">uniforms</term> were worn in all the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1181" type="subject">occupied territories</term>. After checking that the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagon</term> was properly sealed the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">officer</term> notified one of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> employees of our traveller’s presence and
				it was thus <pb n="5" facs="EHRI-ET-WL16560633_05.jpg"/> that he made for the west, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hidden</term> beneath a pile of sacks.</p>
			<p>Being in the dark he could not distinguish night from day, he could just see a little light through the gaps in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagon</term>, so he had no idea of how long the
				journey took. Amongst the sacks in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagon</term>
				he noticed some that contained black [probably <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-429">SS</orgName>]
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1091" type="subject">uniforms</term>. He stayed like this until the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> stopped. When the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">man</term> who had been informed of his presence
				opened the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagon</term> he saw that he was in the
				goods yard of the <foreign xml:lang="fr">Gare de l’Est in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2988507/paris.html"
						>Paris</placeName></foreign>. He was shown the way out of the station and he went straight to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">home</term> of one of his brothers-in-law who lived in
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2988507/paris.html">Paris</placeName>. Having got some money and changed his <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term>, he left the city that evening and went
				to the free [unoccupied] zone, from where he left for <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2658434/switzerland.html"
					>Switzerland</placeName>, along with some other <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-304" type="subject"
					>refugees</term>. His adventure had lasted six weeks.</p>
			<p>I was able to see this <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">man</term> in a <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2658434/switzerland.html">Swiss</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">hospital</term>. He was thirty-three years old, of
				robust appearance, the type who <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">works</term> with
				machines, of nondescript appearance and average intelligence. He scarcely realises his extraordinary luck. He made a good impression
				on me, recounting quite simply the things he had seen, adding nothing that he had not seen personally. He often replied to my
				questions with <q>I don’t know</q>. His accounts of the treatment of Jews in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2802361/kingdom-of-belgium.html">Belgium</placeName> also accord with those of others who have
				arrived here. We should note, too, that he made no mention of his extraordinary odyssey to the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2658434/switzerland.html">Swiss</placeName> authorities when they questioned him. He made no attempt
				whatsoever to make himself interesting to the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2658434/switzerland.html">Swiss</placeName>
				authorities in the hope that he might perhaps obtain some special treatment. Besides all they asked was where he came from. He
				answered <q>from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2996944/lyon.html">Lyon</placeName></q>. No other question having been asked,
				he kept his story to himself.</p>
			<p><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2660646/geneve.html">Geneva</placeName>, <date when="1942-10-10">10 October 1942</date></p>
